<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Surinam bauxite strike ends
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINGSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BAUXITE MINERS in Surinam have returned to work after a two-week strike.
About 2,000 miners were demanding 100 per cent wage increases to keep pace
with inflation, but settled for a rise of 40 per cent.
There is still a threat of industrial action as the workers are seeking
payment for the days they were on strike.
The industry, based on a 1.6m tonnes-a-year refinery and a 30,000 t/y
smelter, accounts for about 70 per cent of the South American republic's
foreign earnings. It is owned by the Aluminum Company of America and
Billiton, a subsidiary of Royal Dutch/Shell.
